{"title_page": "Scott E. Langum", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Scott E. Langum\n| image              = Captain Scott E. Langum.png\n| image_size         = 230px\n| caption            = Scott E. Langum as commanding officer of Coast Guard Air Station Cape Cod\n| birth_name         = Scott Edward Langum\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1970|3|19}}\n| birth_place        = [[Monroe, Washington]], U.S.\n| education          = [[United States Coast Guard Academy]] [[Bachelor of Science|(BS)]] <br> [[University of South Alabama]] [[Master of Public Administration|(MPA)]]<br>[[U.S. Army War College]] [[Strategic studies|(MSS)]]\n| occupation         = [[United States Naval Aviator|U.S. Coast Guard Aviator]]\n| spouse             = {{marriage |Carmen C. Harder |1993}}\n| children           = Kendall Langum<br>\nPaige Langum\n| module             = {{Infobox military person|embed=yes\n| allegiance   = {{flag|United States|1960}}\n| branch       = {{flag|United States Coast Guard}}\n| serviceyears = 1993-present\n| rank         = [[File:US-O6 insignia.svg|20px]] [[Captain (United States O-6)|Captain]]\n| commands      = {{Ubl\n | [[Coast Guard Air Station Houston|USCG Air Station Houston]]\n | [[Coast Guard Air Station Cape Cod|USCG Air Station Cape Cod]]\n }}\n| awards =  [[File:Dfc-usa.jpg|23px]] [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]]\n|\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Scott Edward Langum''' is a [[United States Coast Guard]] [[Naval aviator|aviator]] and [[Commanding officer|commander]], who has served as Deputy Senate Liason for the Coast Guard's congressional engagements with the United States Senate. He is a recipient of the Distinguished Flying Cross for his work in the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina.\n\n==Early life and education==\nLingum was born in 1970 in [[Monroe, Washington]]. He went to the [[United States Coast Guard Academy]] in [[New London, Connecticut]], graduating in 1993 with a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[political science]] and [[government]]. After graduation, he was commissioned as an [[Ensign (rank)|ensign]] in the [[United States Coast Guard]]. He would later graduate from the [[University of South Alabama]] in 2005 with a [[Masters of Public Administration]] degree and the [[U.S. Army War College]] in 2016 with a [[Strategic studies|Master of Strategic Studies]] degree.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://publications.armywarcollege.edu/pubs/857.pdf|title=The Arctic: Has America Been Left In the Cold?|last=Langum|first=Scott E.|date=January 4, 2016|website=Army War College|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Early Coast Guard and helicopter pilot career==\n\nAfter graduation, Langum would serve on the [[USCGC Sundew (WLB-404)|USCGC Sundew]] from 1993 to 1995 based in [[Duluth, Minnesota]]. He then served as the Aids to Naviation Officer for a year from 1995 to 1996 for the Greater Antilles Section in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlanticarea.uscg.mil/Our-Organization/District-1/District-Units/Air-Station-Cape-Cod/Command/|title=Air Station Cape Cod Command|website=www.atlanticarea.uscg.mil|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\nStarting in November 1996, Langum reported to [[Naval Air Station Pensacola]] for [[Naval aviator]] training, graduating in March 1998 and becoming a [[Sikorsky MH-60 Jayhawk|Sikorsky Jayhawk]] pilot. From 1998 to 2002, he served as an HH-60J Aircraft Commander based at [[Coast Guard Air Station Astoria]] in [[Astoria, Oregon]]. Later, he became a MH-60 J [[Flight instructor|Flight Examiner/Fleet Standardization Pilot]] based at the [[Coast Guard Aviation Training Center]] in [[Mobile, Alabama]]. In 2005, he was awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] by [[George W. Bush|President Bush]] for saving 168 lives in HH-60J helicopters during the aftermath of [[Hurricane Katrina]]. Afterwards, between June 2006 and June 2008, he continued his flight instructor career as an MH-60J Flight Examiner and Facility Engineering Department Head based at [[Coast Guard Air Station Sitka]] in [[Sitka, Alaska]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/33688|title=Scott Langum - Recipient -|website=valor.militarytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==Senate and Coast Guard commander==\n\nAfter his flight instructor career, he became a Military Liaison to the [[United States Senate]], serving as a Deputy Senate Liaison and responsible for facilitating the Coast Guard\u2019s congressional engagements with the Senate.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2010, he became an Operations Officer at [[Coast Guard Air Station Traverse City]] in [[Traverse City, Michigan]], moving up to become an Executive Officer at the base. In 2013, he became Commanding Officer of [[Coast Guard Air Station Houston]] as the previous commander,  Eric S. Gleason, was leaving for the [[Naval War College]] to attend Senior Service School. Langum served as commander of the base until June 2015 when he left to study at the [[U.S. Army War College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coastguardnews.com/coast-guard-aviators-welcome-new-commander-in-houston/2013/06/20/|title=Coast Guard aviators welcome new commander in Houston {{!}} Coast Guard News|website=coastguardnews.com|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating from the Army War College in 2016, he became the [[J35 Division Chief]] of the [[U.S. Northern Command]] based in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]]. In 2018, he was promoted to Commanding Officer of [[Coast Guard Air Station Cape Cod]] based at [[Joint Base Cape Cod]] in [[Massachusetts]], which he is serving today.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Personal life==\n\nLangum married Carmen C. Harder on May 29, 1993 in her home state of [[Washington]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.digitalarchives.wa.gov/Record/View/2023366CAD007A5E9B920C66298B496D|title=Whitman County Auditor, Marriage Records, 1872-2002 - Scott Edward Langum - Carmen Caroline Harder|website=Washington State Archives, Digital Archives|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> They have two daughters.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:United States Coast Guard Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Monroe, Washington]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Scott E. Langum\n| image              = Captain Scott E. Langum.png\n| image_size         = 230px\n| caption            = Scott E. Langum as commanding officer of Coast Guard Air Station Cape Cod\n| birth_name         = Scott Edward Langum\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1970|3|19}}\n| birth_place        = [[Monroe, Washington]], U.S.\n| education          = [[United States Coast Guard Academy]] [[Bachelor of Science|(BS)]] <br> [[University of South Alabama]] [[Master of Public Administration|(MPA)]]<br>[[U.S. Army War College]] [[Strategic studies|(MSS)]]\n| occupation         = [[United States Naval Aviator|U.S. Coast Guard Aviator]]\n| spouse             = {{marriage |Carmen C. Harder |1993}}\n| children           = Kendall Langum<br>\nPaige Langum\n| module             = {{Infobox military person|embed=yes\n| allegiance   = {{flag|United States|1960}}\n| branch       = {{flag|United States Coast Guard}}\n| serviceyears = 1993-present\n| rank         = [[File:US-O6 insignia.svg|20px]] [[Captain (United States O-6)|Captain]]\n| commands      = {{Ubl\n | [[Coast Guard Air Station Houston|USCG Air Station Houston]]\n | [[Coast Guard Air Station Cape Cod|USCG Air Station Cape Cod]]\n }}\n| awards =  [[File:Dfc-usa.jpg|23px]] [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]]\n|\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Scott Edward Langum''' is a [[United States Coast Guard]] [[Naval aviator|aviator]] and [[Commanding officer|commander]], who has served as Deputy Senate Liason for the Coast Guard's congressional engagements with the United States Senate. He is a recipient of the Distinguished Flying Cross for his work in the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina.\n\n==Early life and education==\nLingum was born in 1970 in [[Monroe, Washington]]. He went to the [[United States Coast Guard Academy]] in [[New London, Connecticut]], graduating in 1993 with a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[political science]] and [[government]]. After graduation, he was commissioned as an [[Ensign (rank)|Ensign]] in the [[United States Coast Guard]]. He would later graduate from the [[University of South Alabama]] in 2005 with a [[Masters of Public Administration]] degree and the [[U.S. Army War College]] in 2016 with a [[Strategic studies|Master of Strategic Studies]] degree.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://publications.armywarcollege.edu/pubs/857.pdf|title=The Arctic: Has America Been Left In the Cold?|last=Langum|first=Scott E.|date=January 4, 2016|website=Army War College|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Early Coast Guard and helicopter pilot career==\n\nAfter graduation, Langum would serve on the [[USCGC Sundew (WLB-404)|USCGC Sundew]] from 1993 to 1995 based in [[Duluth, Minnesota]]. He then served as the Aids to Naviation Officer for a year from 1995 to 1996 for the Greater Antilles Section in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlanticarea.uscg.mil/Our-Organization/District-1/District-Units/Air-Station-Cape-Cod/Command/|title=Air Station Cape Cod Command|website=www.atlanticarea.uscg.mil|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\nStarting in November 1996, Langum reported to [[Naval Air Station Pensacola]] for [[Naval aviator]] training, graduating in March 1998 and becoming a [[Sikorsky MH-60 Jayhawk|Sikorsky Jayhawk]] pilot. From 1998 to 2002, he served as an HH-60J Aircraft Commander based at [[Coast Guard Air Station Astoria]] in [[Astoria, Oregon]]. Later, he became a MH-60 J [[Flight instructor|Flight Examiner/Fleet Standardization Pilot]] based at the [[Coast Guard Aviation Training Center]] in [[Mobile, Alabama]]. In 2005, he was awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] by [[George W. Bush|President Bush]] for saving 168 lives in HH-60J helicopters during the aftermath of [[Hurricane Katrina]]. Afterwards, between June 2006 and June 2008, he continued his flight instructor career as an MH-60J Flight Examiner and Facility Engineering Department Head based at [[Coast Guard Air Station Sitka]] in [[Sitka, Alaska]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/33688|title=Scott Langum - Recipient -|website=valor.militarytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==Senate and Coast Guard commander==\n\nAfter his flight instructor career, he became a Military Liaison to the [[United States Senate]], serving as a Deputy Senate Liaison and responsible for facilitating the Coast Guard\u2019s congressional engagements with the Senate.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2010, he became an Operations Officer at [[Coast Guard Air Station Traverse City]] in [[Traverse City, Michigan]], moving up to become an Executive Officer at the base. In 2013, he became Commanding Officer of [[Coast Guard Air Station Houston]] as the previous commander,  Eric S. Gleason, was leaving for the [[Naval War College]] to attend Senior Service School. Langum served as commander of the base until June 2015 when he left to study at the [[U.S. Army War College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coastguardnews.com/coast-guard-aviators-welcome-new-commander-in-houston/2013/06/20/|title=Coast Guard aviators welcome new commander in Houston {{!}} Coast Guard News|website=coastguardnews.com|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating from the Army War College in 2016, he became the [[J35 Division Chief]] of the [[U.S. Northern Command]] based in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]]. In 2018, he was promoted to Commanding Officer of [[Coast Guard Air Station Cape Cod]] based at [[Joint Base Cape Cod]] in [[Massachusetts]], which he is serving today.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Personal life==\n\nLangum married Carmen C. Harder on May 29, 1993 in her home state of [[Washington]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.digitalarchives.wa.gov/Record/View/2023366CAD007A5E9B920C66298B496D|title=Whitman County Auditor, Marriage Records, 1872-2002 - Scott Edward Langum - Carmen Caroline Harder|website=Washington State Archives, Digital Archives|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> They have two daughters.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:United States Coast Guard Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Monroe, Washington]]\n", "name_user": "Cuprum17", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and education:caps", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scott_E._Langum"}
{"title_page": "Maria Haller", "text_new": "'''Maria de Jesus Haller''' (1923&ndash;2006), was [[Angola]]'s first female [[ambassador]]. She participated in Angola's struggle for independence from its [[colonial power]], [[Portugal]], and she was a teacher, a journalist and a writer.<ref name=\"angop\">{{cite news |url=http://www.angop.ao/angola/pt_pt/mobile/noticias/sociedade/2006/9/42/Morreu-Maria-Haller-primeira-embaixadora-Angola,ba29b3d7-4577-4dba-90e8-9847fb1a8f9a.html |title=Morreu Maria Haller, primeira embaixadora de Angola |language=Portuguese |date=18 October 2006 |publisher=Angola Press Agency |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe was born Maria de Jesus Nunes Da Silva in 1923, the daughter of a 12-year-old plantation worker who had been raped by the plantation owner.<ref name=\"1000pw\">{{cite book |title=1000 Peacewomen Across the Globe |page=924 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/1000_Peacewomen_Across_the_Globe/kIQnAQAAMAAJ |publisher=Scalo Verlag Ac |isbn=978-3039390397 |year=2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Le_dos_de_ma_Lumi%C3%A8re/z_suDwAAQBAJ |title=Le dos de ma lumi\u00e8re |language=French |first=Colinette |last=Haller |isbn=9789895151738 |publisher=Chiado Editeur}}</ref> When she was three, her father sent her to be raised in his native Portugal.<ref name=\"1000pw\"/> At fifteen she briefly reunited with her mother and became inspired to pursue activism and politics.<ref name=\"1000pw\"/>\n\nAround 1955 she married Swiss businessman Jean Rodolphe de Haller. While living in [[L\u00e9opoldville]] in colonial [[Belgian Congo]], she met fellow Angolans living in exile who opposed Portugal's oppression of the Black population of Angola.<ref name=\"1000pw\"/> After returning to Europe, Haller stayed in contact with the group and, around 1965, was asked to represent the [[MPLA]] (People's Movement for the Liberation of Angola) in [[Cairo]].<ref name=\"cremado\">{{cite news |url=http://www.angop.ao/angola/pt_pt/noticias/politica/2006/9/43/Suica-Corpo-embaixadora-Maria-Haller-cremado-hoje-Genebra,f7c11527-75fd-452b-af08-9d82221baef0.html |title=Su\u00ed\u00e7a: Corpo de ex-embaixadora Maria Haller cremado hoje em Genebra |language=Portuguese |date=24 October 2006 |publisher=Angola Press Agency |access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Hist%C3%B3ria_do_MPLA_1940_1966/-isvAQAAIAAJ |page=334 |title=Hist\u00f3ria do MPLA: 1940-1966 |language=Portuguese |author=Comiss\u00e3o para a Elabora\u00e7\u00e3o da Hist\u00f3ria |publisher=Movimento Popular de Liberta\u00e7\u00e3o de Angola |year=2008}}</ref> She faced sexism in this role, with Egyptian officials denying her access to radio stations until she and [[Agostinho Neto]] threatened to leave Egypt.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://word.world-citizenship.org/wp-archive/1481 |title=Maria de Jesus Haller \u2013 Angola |date=3 September 2007 |website=World People's Blog |publisher=World-Wide Asian-Eurasian Human Rights Forum |access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter 13 years of [[Angolan War of Independence|war]], Angola gained its independence on 11 November 1975 with Agostinho Neto as its first president. In 1978, Haller became Angola's first female ambassador and was sent to [[Stockholm]] to represent her country in the [[Kingdom of Sweden]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Angolanskor |first1=Birgitta |last1=Lagerstr\u00f6m |first2=Hillevi |last2=Nilsson |isbn=9185584436 |year=1993 |publisher=Afrikagrupperna |language=Swedish}}</ref> She later became director of the Asia and Oceania Department in Angola's [[Ministry of External Relations (Angola)|Ministry of External Relations]].<ref name=\"cremado\"/>\n\nShe was a member of the Union of Angolan Writers (UEA) and in 1988 contributed a children's story to the union's ''Ac\u00e1cia Rubra'' (''Rubber Tree'') anthology.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ueangola.com/criticas-e-ensaios/item/301-surgimento-e-desenvolvimento-da-literatura-infantil-angolana-p%C3%B3s-independ%C3%AAncia |first=Maria Celestina |last=Fernandes |title=Surgimento e Desenvolvimento da Literatura Infantil Angolana P\u00f3s-Independ\u00eancia  |language=Portuguese |publisher=Uni\u00e3o dos Escritores Angolanos (UEA) |access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://aflit.arts.uwa.edu.au/FEMECalireLU.html |title=Women Writing Africa: A Bibliography of Lusophone Women Writers |first=Tony |last=Simoes da Silva |publisher=University of Wollongong, Australia |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHaller died on 18 October 2006 in [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]], after a prolonged illness.<ref name=\"angop\"/> Her funeral was held in Angola.<ref name=\"cremado\"/>\n\n==Works==\n*{{cite book|chapter=F\u00e1...pe...l\u00e1\u00e1\u00e1!!! |title=Ac\u00e1cia Rubra |publisher= Uni\u00e3o dos Escritores Angolanos (UEA) |year=1988}} (anthology of children's stories)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haller, Maria de Jesus}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:MPLA]]\n[[Category:Angolan women activists]]\n[[Category:Angolan activists]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Angola to Sweden]]\n[[Category:Women ambassadors]]\n[[Category:Angolan women writers\u200e]]\n[[Category:Angolan writers\u200e]]\n[[Category:Women children's writers\u200e]]\n[[Category:Children's writers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Maria de Jesus Haller''' (1923&ndash;2006), was [[Angola]]'s first female [[ambassador]]. She participated in Angola's struggle for independence from its [[colonial power]], [[Portugal]], and she was a teacher, a journalist and a writer.<ref name=\"angop\">{{cite news |url=http://www.angop.ao/angola/pt_pt/mobile/noticias/sociedade/2006/9/42/Morreu-Maria-Haller-primeira-embaixadora-Angola,ba29b3d7-4577-4dba-90e8-9847fb1a8f9a.html |title=Morreu Maria Haller, primeira embaixadora de Angola |language=Portuguese |date=18 October 2006 |publisher=Angola Press Agency |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe was born Maria de Jesus Nunes Da Silva in 1923, the daughter of a 12-year-old plantation worker who had been raped by the plantation owner.<ref name=\"1000pw\">{{cite book |title=1000 Peacewomen Across the Globe |page=924 |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/1000_Peacewomen_Across_the_Globe/kIQnAQAAMAAJ |publisher=Scalo Verlag Ac |isbn=978-3039390397 |year=2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Le_dos_de_ma_Lumi%C3%A8re/z_suDwAAQBAJ |title=Le dos de ma lumi\u00e8re |language=French |first=Colinette |last=Haller |isbn=9789895151738 |publisher=Chiado Editeur}}</ref> When she was three, her father sent her to be raised in his native Portugal.<ref name=\"1000pw\"/> At fifteen she briefly reunited with her mother and became inspired to pursue activism and politics.<ref name=\"1000pw\"/>\n\nAround 1955 she married Swiss businessman Jean Rodolphe de Haller. While living in [[L\u00e9opoldville]] in colonial [[Belgian Congo]], she met fellow Angolans living in exile who opposed Portugal's oppression of the Black population of Angola.<ref name=\"1000pw\"/> After returning to Europe, Haller stayed in contact with the group and, around 1965, was asked to represent the [[MPLA]] (People's Movement for the Liberation of Angola) in [[Cairo]].<ref name=\"cremado\">{{cite news |url=http://www.angop.ao/angola/pt_pt/noticias/politica/2006/9/43/Suica-Corpo-embaixadora-Maria-Haller-cremado-hoje-Genebra,f7c11527-75fd-452b-af08-9d82221baef0.html |title=Su\u00ed\u00e7a: Corpo de ex-embaixadora Maria Haller cremado hoje em Genebra |language=Portuguese |date=24 October 2006 |publisher=Angola Press Agency |access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Hist%C3%B3ria_do_MPLA_1940_1966/-isvAQAAIAAJ |page=334 |title= History of the MPLA: 1940-1966 |author=Commission for the Elaboration of History |publisher=Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola}}</ref> She faced sexism in this role, with Egyptian officials denying her access to radio stations until she and [[Agostinho Neto]] threatened to leave Egypt.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://word.world-citizenship.org/wp-archive/1481 |title=Maria de Jesus Haller \u2013 Angola |date=3 September 2007 |website=World People's Blog |publisher=World-Wide Asian-Eurasian Human Rights Forum |access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter 13 years of [[Angolan War of Independence|war]], Angola gained its independence on 11 November 1975 with Agostinho Neto as its first president. In 1978, Haller became Angola's first female ambassador and was sent to [[Stockholm]] to represent her country in the [[Kingdom of Sweden]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Angolanskor |first1=Birgitta |last1=Lagerstr\u00f6m |first2=Hillevi |last2=Nilsson |isbn=9185584436 |year=1993 |publisher=Afrikagrupperna |language=Swedish}}</ref> She later became director of the Asia and Oceania Department in Angola's [[Ministry of External Relations (Angola)|Ministry of External Relations]].<ref name=\"cremado\"/>\n\nShe was a member of the Union of Angolan Writers (UEA) and in 1988 contributed a children's story to the union's ''Ac\u00e1cia Rubra'' (''Rubber Tree'') anthology.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ueangola.com/criticas-e-ensaios/item/301-surgimento-e-desenvolvimento-da-literatura-infantil-angolana-p%C3%B3s-independ%C3%AAncia |first=Maria Celestina |last=Fernandes |title=Surgimento e Desenvolvimento da Literatura Infantil Angolana P\u00f3s-Independ\u00eancia  |language=Portuguese |publisher=Uni\u00e3o dos Escritores Angolanos (UEA) |access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://aflit.arts.uwa.edu.au/FEMECalireLU.html |title=Women Writing Africa: A Bibliography of Lusophone Women Writers |first=Tony |last=Simoes da Silva |publisher=University of Wollongong, Australia |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHaller died on 18 October 2006 in [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]], after a prolonged illness.<ref name=\"angop\"/> Her funeral was held in Angola.<ref name=\"cremado\"/>\n\n==Works