 GAA|Drom-Inch]]\n|0-06\n|6\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2012\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Aidan McCormack]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[File:Colours of Cavan.svg|border|20px]] [[Thurles Sarsfields GAA|Thurles Sarsfields]]\n|1-06\n|9\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Johnny Ryan\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[File:Colours of Limerick.svg|border|20px]] [[Drom-Inch GAA|Drom-Inch]]\n|0-09\n|9\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2013\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Noel McGrath (hurler)|Noel McGrath]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[File:Colours of Mayo.svg|border|20px]] [[Loughmore-Castleiney GAA|Loughmore-Castleiney]]\n|0-07\n|7\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Michael Heffernan (hurler)|Michael Heffernan]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[File:Colours of Dublin.svg|border|20px]] [[Nenagh \u00c9ire \u00d3g GAA|Nenagh \u00c9ire \u00d3g]]\n|0-07\n|7\n|-\n|2014\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Pa Bourke]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[File:Colours of Cavan.svg|border|20px]] [[Thurles Sarsfields GAA|Thurles Sarsfields]]\n|1-03\n|6\n|-\n|2015\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Michael Heffernan (hurler)|Michael Heffernan]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[File:Colours of Dublin.svg|border|20px]] [[Nenagh \u00c9ire \u00d3g GAA|Nenagh \u00c9ire \u00d3g]]\n|1-04\n|7\n|-\n|2016\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Pa Bourke]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[File:Colours of Cavan.svg|border|20px]] [[Thurles Sarsfields GAA|Thurles Sarsfields]]\n|0-09\n|9\n|-\n|2017\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Aidan McCormack]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[File:Colours of Cavan.svg|border|20px]] [[Thurles Sarsfields GAA|Thurles Sarsfields]]\n|0-09\n|9\n|}\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of Tipperary Senior Hurling Championship winners]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hoganstand.com/Tipperary Tipperary on Hoganstand]\n*[http://www.clubgaa.ie/tipperary/index.htm Tipperary Club GAA]\n*[http://www.premierview.ie Premierview]\n\n{{Tipperary Senior Hurling Championship}}\n\n[[Category:Tipperary Senior Hurling Championship| ]]\n[[Category:Tipperary GAA club championships|Hurl]]\n[[Category:Senior hurling county championships]]\n[[Category:Hurling competitions in County Tipperary|1]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox GAA tournament\n| name                 = Tipperary Senior Hurling Championship\n| currentlyrunning     = [[2019 Tipperary Senior Hurling Championship]]\n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| irish                = \n| code                 = [[Hurling]]\n| founded              = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1887}}\n| region               = [[File:Colours of Tipperary.svg|20px|border]] [[County Tipperary|Tipperary]]\n| trophy               = Dan Breen Cup\n| teams                = 32\n| title holders        = [[Borris-Ileigh GAA|Borris-Ileigh]]\n| currentordinal       = 7\n| super                = th\n| most titles          = [[File:Colours of Cavan.svg|20px|border]] [[Thurles Sarsfields GAA|Thurles Sarsfields]]\n| mostordinal          = 36\n| sponsors             = Tipperary Water\n| tv                   = [[TG4]] (final only)\n| motto                = \n| website              = [https://tipperary.gaa.ie/ Official website]\n}}\nThe '''Tipperary Senior Hurling Championship''' (known for sponsorship reasons as the '''Tipperary Water Tipperary County Senior Hurling Championship''') is an annual [[hurling]] competition organised by the [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary County Board]] of the [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] since 1887 for the top hurling teams in the [[County Tipperary|county of Tipperary]] in [[Ireland]].\n\nThe series of games are played during the summer and autumn months with the county final currently being played at [[Semple Stadium]] in October. The prize for the winning team is the Dan Breen Cup. Initially played as a knock-out competition on a divisional basis, the championship currently features a group stage followed by a knock-out stage.\n\nThe Tipperary County Championship is an integral part of the wider [[Munster Senior Club Hurling Championship]]. The winners of the Tipperary county final join the champions of the other four hurling counties to contest the provincial championship.\n\n32 teams currently participate in the Tipperary County Championship. The title has been won at least once by 25 different teams. The all-time record-holders are [[Thurles Sarsfields GAA|Thurles Sarsfields]], who have won a total of 36 titles.\n\n[[Clonoulty-Rossmore GAA|Clonoulty-Rossmore]] won the [[2018 Tipperary Senior Hurling Championship|2018 Championship]], their first championship since 1997 after a 0-23 to 2-13 win against [[Nenagh \u00c9ire \u00d3g GAA|Nenagh \u00c9ire \u00d3g]] in the final.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/2018/1021/1005701-clonoulty-rossmore-end-21-year-wait-for-tipp-glory/ |title =Clonoulty-Rossmore end 21-year wait for Tipp glory|date=21 October 2018|work=RTE Sport|accessdate=22 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/2018/1021/1005747-the-gaa-club-is-the-lifeblood-of-the-whole-of-ireland/ |title ='The GAA club is the lifeblood of the whole of Ireland'|date=21 October 2018|work=RTE Sport|accessdate=22 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/sport/gaa/clonoulty-rossmore-win-first-title-in-21-years-after-thrilling-final-success-877207.html |title =Clonoulty-Rossmore win first title in 21 years after thrilling final success|date=21 October 2018|work=Irish Examiner|accessdate=22 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Beginnings===\n\nFollowing the foundation of the [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] (GAA) in 1884, new rules for [[Gaelic football]] and [[hurling]] were drawn up and published in the ''[[United Irishman (1848 newspaper)|United Irishman]]'' newspaper. County committees were quickly established, with the [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary County Board]] affiliating in 1886. Over the course of the following year, 130 clubs registered with the GAA in Tipperary, making it the strongest county in the country. After difficulties in organising the early championships, the title has been awarded every year except on one occasion since 1894. Civil unrest at the height of the [[Irish War of Independence|War of Independence]] resulted in the 1920 championship being cancelled.\n\n===Team dominance===\n\nSince the beginning, the championship has seen periods of dominance by various teams. [[Boherlahen-Dualla GAA|Tubberadora]] became the preeminent team  of the first decade, before being superseded by [[Thurles Sarsfields GAA|Thurles Sarsfields]]. After winning the inaugural title in 1887, the [[Thurles]]-based club won six championships from a possible nine between 1904 and 1911. [[Toomevara GAA|Toomevara]] made their first big breakthrough in 1910 and won titles at regular intervals over the course of the next twenty years. [[Boherlahen-Dualla GAA|Boherlahen-Dualla]] won the first of four successive championship titles in 1915 and won a grand total of ten up to and including the 1941 championship. Thurles Sarsfields bounced back in 1929 after an eleven-year period in the doldrums. Over the course of the next 45 years the club established itself as the standard bearer of club hurling in Tipperary by winning 21 titles during this period. The club reached its peak by winning ten titles in eleven championship seasons between 1955 and 1965. [[Roscrea GAA|Roscrea]] won their first championship in 1968 before completing a three-in-a-row in 1970. The club won further titles in 1972, 1973 and 1980. [[Moneygall GAA|Moneygall]] and [[Kilruane MacDonagh's GAA|Kilruane MacDonagh's]] shared five titles between 1975 and 1979, while [[Borris-Ileigh GAA|Borris-Ileigh]] won three titles throughout the 1980s. After failing to win a championship in over thirty years, Toomevara returned to the top table in 1992. Over the course of the next sixteen years the club claimed 11 championship titles. Thurles Sarsfields also returned to their winning ways after a 31-year barren spell by claiming the 2005 championship. They have since become the most successful team of the 21st century by winning eight championships.\n\n==Format==\n\nThe Tipperary senior hurling championship is probably the most complicated system in Ireland as it has striven to accommodate from 25 to, currently, 32 teams. A knockout divisional system and group backdoor system has been introduced to accommodate these teams. Before the new system, the county championship was run on a divisional basis with the teams in the divisional finals going into the county quarter-finals and proceeding from there.\n\nA new format is to be introduced in 2014 with the county championship divided into two sections of 16 teams each, the sections determined by clubs' placings in the 2013 championship. Each section will be divided into four groups of four teams with games played on a round robin basis. The top two teams in each Section 1 group, and the top team in each Section 2 group, qualify for the knockout stages, as do the four divisional champions. The bottom team in each Section 1 group is relegated to Section 2, and the top team in each Section 2 group is promoted to Section 1. The bottom teams in each of the Section 2 groups face relegation play-offs, with two teams relegated to the [[Tipperary Intermediate Hurling Championship|Intermediate Championship]]. The Intermediate champions move up to Section 2. Thus in 2015 there will be 31 teams in the Senior Championship.<ref>[http://tipperary.gaa.ie/latestnews/tipperarygaascene-january22nd2013 Tipperary GAA] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130125235935/http://tipperary.gaa.ie/latestnews/tipperarygaascene-january22nd2013 |date=2013-01-25 }} website, \"Latest News\", 22 January 2013</ref>\n\n==Sponsorship==\n\nFor four years between 2013 and 2016, the championship was sponsored by Clean Ireland Recycling.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nationalist.ie/news/gaelic-games/141462/Clean-Ireland-Recycling-in-new-sponsorship.html|title=Clean Ireland Recycling in new sponsorship deal|publisher=The Nationalist|date=27 June 2013|accessdate=29 March 2018|first=|last=}}</ref> In August 2016, the Tipperary County Board announced that they had signed a three-year sponsorship deal with [[Tipperary Water]]. The company has since sponsored all of Tipperary's adult county championships.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nenaghguardian.ie/news/roundup/articles/2016/08/22/4125316-tipperary-water-announces-three-year-sponsorship-deal-with-tipperary-gaa/|title=Tipperary Water announces three year sponsorship deal with Tipperary GAA|publisher=Nenagh Guardian|date=22 August 2016|accessdate=29 March 2018|first=|last=}}</ref>\n\n==Qualification for subsequent competitions==\n\nThe Tipperary Senior Hurling Championship winners qualify for the subsequent [[Munster Senior Club Hurling Championship]]. This place is reserved for club teams only as divisional and amalgamated teams are not allowed in the provincial championship.\n\n==Venues==\n===Early rounds===\n[[File:Semple1.jpg|thumb|Semple Stadium in Thurles.]]\nFixtures in the group stage and early knock-out rounds of the championship are usually played at a neutral venue that is deemed halfway between the participating teams. Some of the more common venues include [[MacDonagh Park]], [[St. Cronan's Park]] and [[Toomevara GAA|St. Michael's Park]]. All games from the quarter-finals onward are played at [[Semple Stadium]].\n\n=== Final ===\n\nThe final is usually played at Semple Stadium, previously Thurles Sportsfield.\n\n==Managers==\n\n[[Manager (Gaelic Games)|Managers]] in the Tipperary Championship are involved in the day-to-day running of the team, including the training, team selection, and sourcing of players. Their influence varies from club-to-club and is related to the individual club committees. The manager is assisted by a team of two or three selectors and a backroom team consisting of various coaches.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|+ Winning managers (1999\u2013present)\n|-\n!Manager\n!Team\n!Wins\n!Winning years\n|-\n|Tommy Maher\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Thurles Sarsfields GAA|Thurles Sarsfields]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|2014, 2015, 2016, 2017\n|-\n|[[Michael Gleeson (hurler)|Michael Gleeson]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Thurles Sarsfields GAA|Thurles Sarsfields]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|2009, 2010\n|-\n|Tom Ryan\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Toomevara GAA|Toomevara]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|1999\n|-\n|[[Pad Joe Whelehan]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Toomevara GAA|Toomevara]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|2000\n|-\n|[[Se\u00e1n Stack]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Toomevara GAA|Toomevara]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|2001\n|-\n|[[John Leahy (hurler)|John Leahy]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Mullinahone GAA|Mullinahone]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|2002\n|-\n|Michael Connolly\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Toomevara GAA|Toomevara]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|2003\n|-\n|Se\u00e1n Hehir\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Toomevara GAA|Toomevara]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|2004\n|-\n|[[Ger Cunningham (Limerick hurler)|Ger Cunningham]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Thurles Sarsfields GAA|Thurles Sarsfields]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|2005\n|-\n|[[Pat Herbert]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Toomevara GAA|Toomevara]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|2006\n|-\n|\u00c9amonn Sweeney\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Loughmore-Castleiney GAA|Loughmore-Castleiney]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|2007\n|-\n|Paddy McCormack\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Toomevara GAA|Toomevara]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|2008\n|-\n|Teddy Kennedy\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Drom-Inch GAA|Drom-Inch]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|2011\n|-\n|S\u00e9amus Quinn\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Thurles Sarsfields GAA|Thurles Sarsfields]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|2012\n|-\n|Declan Laffan\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Loughmore-Castleiney GAA|Loughmore-Castleiney]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|2013\n|-\n|[[John Devane]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Clonoulty-Rossmore GAA|Clonoulty-Rossmore]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|2018\n|-\n|Johnny Kelly\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Borris-Ileigh GAA|Borris-Ileigh]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|2019\n|}\n\n==Trophy==\n\nThe winning team is presented with the Dan Breen Cup. A native of [[Donohill]], [[Dan Breen]] (1894-1969) was a [[Volunteer (Irish republican)|volunteer]] in the [[Irish Republican Army]] during the [[Irish War of Independence]] and the [[Irish Civil War]]. In later years, he was a [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] politician.\n\n==Top winners==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"background:silver;\" |\n! style=\"background:silver;\" | '''Team'''\n! style=\"background:silver;\" | '''Winner'''\n! style=\"background:silver;\" | '''Winning Years'''\n! style=\"background:silver;\" | '''Runners-up'''\n! style=\"background:silver;\" | '''Years Runners-up'''\n|- \n| 1\n| [[File:Flag of the counties of Cavan and Laois.svg|25px]] [[Thurles Sarsfields]]\n| 36\n| 1887, 1904, 1906, 1907, 1908, 1909, 1911, 1929, 1935, 1936, 1938, 1939, 1942, 1944, 1945, 1946, 1952, 1955, 1956, 1957, 1958, 1959, 1961, 1962, 1963, 1964, 1965, 1974, 2005, 2009, 2010, 2012, 2014, 2015, 2016, [[2017 Tipperary Senior Hurling Championship|2017]]\n| 10\n| 1894, 1960, 1968, 1970, 1979, 1992, 2000, 2001, 2002, 2003\n|-\n| 2\n| [[File:Gort GAA colours.png|25px]] [[Toomevara GAA|Toomevara]]\n| 21\n| 1890, 1910, 1912, 1913, 1914, 1919, 1923, 1930, 1931, 1960, 1992, 1993, 1994, 1998, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2003, 2004, 2006, 2008\n| 10\n| 1889, 1911, 1916, 1917, 1918, 1925, 1929, 1958, 1961, 1996\n|- \n| 3\n| [[File:Flag of Pretoria, South Africa.svg|25px]] [[Moycarkey-Borris GAA|Moycarkey-Borris]]\n| 12\n| 1899, 1900, 1903, 1905, 1926, 1932, 1933, 1934, 1937, 1940, 1982, 1984\n| 3\n| 1931, 1943, 1962\n|- \n| 4\n| [[File:Tipperary colours.PNG|25px]] [[Boherlahan-Dualla GAA|B